        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>No. 3719</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">OFFICE OF THE CHIEF RABBI.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName>, <date>August 1<hi rend="sup"
                        >st</hi> 5622</date></p>
            <p>Revd &amp; Dear Sir/</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I have yet<lb/> to express my sincere thanks to<lb/> you for your
                very kind congratulations<lb/> on my son's promotion. I hope<lb/> with his talents
                he will prove an<lb/> able &amp; zealous worker in the vine-<lb/>yard of the Lord.
                He has as yet,<lb/> much to learn &amp; to study—but<lb/> at a later period I think
                he<lb/> will contribute to your paper.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Concerning your affairs with<lb/> your agent, <persName>Mr John
                    Joel</persName> I<lb/> have made accurate inquiries.<lb/> He had been insured in
                the Alliance</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Insurance office, &amp; I have been<lb/> told on very good authority, that he<lb/>
                has received from them the sum<lb/> of £1200. I have earnestly spoken<lb/> to him
                about your just claims—<lb/> he has answered me that he has<lb/> the sum of £15-3-8
                for you in<lb/> hand which he will hand to your<lb/> order. Altho' he was insured
                to<lb/> a large amount, he says that<lb/> if he has liquidated his own debts<lb/> he
                shall have nothing left &amp; as<lb/> he had not received any orders<lb/> from you
                to injure his books<lb/> in <placeName>London</placeName> he thought that you<lb/>
                had probably insured them in <del><placeName>London</placeName></del><lb/>
                <placeName>America</placeName>. Perhaps an<lb/> application to the Alliance
                Insurance</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Office might be advisable, to write<lb/> to <persName>Mr Maclagan</persName>, the Secretary<lb/>
                <placeName>Bartholomew Lane</placeName> ask whether your<lb/> books were specified
                among the stock<lb/> that was insured &amp; paid for.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have since then received a communication from <persName>Mr<lb/>
                    Samuel Solomon</persName>, stating that he had<lb/> been appointed your agent.
                He can<lb/> be of much service to recommend<lb/> the adoption of your Bible in
                the<lb/> Free School, of which he is the <hi rend="underline">paid</hi><lb/>
                secretary. I have spoken often<lb/> &amp; much in favour of your Bible;<lb/> &amp;
                shall always continue to do so.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have been told that the<lb/> Society for Diffusion of
                Religious<lb/> Knowledge are likely to take a thousand</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>copies of your Bible, if you can give<lb/> them at 2/3 each—bound I think it
                advisable<lb/> for you to enter into communication<lb/> upon the subject with
                    <persName>N. S. Joseph<lb/> Esq.</persName> The Secretary, East India<lb/>
                Chambers, <placeName>Leadenbell St.</placeName></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I highly<lb/> appreciate your unremitting exertions<lb/> for the
                spiritual welfare of our<lb/> brethren in the 'land of trouble'<lb/>
                <add>וה' יערה רוחו ממרום וידרך שלום אל עמו ישעיהו לב טו</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Revd &amp; Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Yours faithfully</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">&amp;c &amp;c &amp;c <persName role="author">N Adler
                Sr</persName></p>
        </body>
